Moralische Dilemmata for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the US government represents a massive bailout for the creditors of these institutions, whose losses have grown ever larger in light of falling housing prices.
Now that the government is completely on the hook for Fannies and Freddies' debts, American taxpayers will have to foot the bill for whatever is not covered by the insufficient funds of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in what is openly described as the most capitalist country in the world?
Doesn't the time-honored principles of capitalism hold that those who believed in the housing bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers have to suffer from the mistakes of others?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly outlined.
But they are not.
Especially unclear is whether the bailout will actually cost US taxpayers in the end. It might prevent further systemic effects that could bring the financial sector, and thus the world economy, to its knees.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify, one cannot conclude that they do not exist.
Furthermore, the mortgage-backed securities issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as being backed by an implicit guarantee of the US government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a rescue by the US government could undermine confidence in government bonds and, because they are often associated with these, also in other financial instruments.
The problems extend far beyond the US economy.
The world economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative booms and busts in asset values, which introduce questions of confidence as well as fairness into the equation.
Similar booms in the housing sector are currently coming to an end in many other countries, and they may face the same trials – and the same moral dilemmas – that the US economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem is not just the housing markets.
The stock markets are also affected.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of 5 between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The BSE Sensex in India rose by a factor of 5 in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar highs and crashes of stock markets have occurred in many other countries as well.
As long as they continued, the preceding boom phases led to overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a loss of confidence could grip the world economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selective bailouts may be necessary – not to prop up the markets, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust; there is no way to predict how people will react when help is absent as markets collapse.
People's reactions to such events depend on their emotions and sense of justice.
The described altitude flights and crashes have caused a great redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested on the stock exchange or real estate market fared well or poorly depending on the timing.
People will assess the fairness of these results based on what they were told and the implicit promises derived from it.
What did people in all these countries learn about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
Es gibt leider keinen Weg, das herauszufinden.
Die Politik kann lediglich allgemein reagieren und nicht alle Fälle einzeln behandeln.
Wir wissen, dass das Wirtschaftswachstum der jüngsten Zeit in vielen Ländern spektakulär war.
Aber wurden die Kapitalanlagen in ihre Märkte zu teuer verkauft?
Haben zynische Verkäufer hier und anderswo die Menschen zu der Annahme verführt, dass die Boomzeiten Wohlstand für alle bringen würden?
Surely, there has been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – but most of the losers at this game do not hang on the edge of starvation.
Yet, we cannot conclude from this that all their losses should be left entirely unaddressed.
The nagging problem is one of "honesty and trust".
National economies flourish only when "honesty and trust" prevail.
The current situation, where speculative highs have driven the world economy – and now, after their collapse, have pushed it into recession – suggests that people who have promoted certain investment opportunities have acted against honesty and trust.
Take the investors who underwrote the securities of Fannie and Freddie.
Although the US government never officially promised to bail them out in case of trouble, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to evaluate their strength in an annual report.
But this agency never admitted that there was a housing bubble.
The top officials of the government never issued a warning.
Can we therefore really claim that investors have to bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is discovering the power and transformation of capitalism, including national economies.
But capitalism relies on trust and faith.
An unfairly perceived treatment can be fatal for economic growth, as it means people will lose their trust in companies and therefore be less willing to provide them with their valuable capital and labor.
Is such a result morally preferable to a bailout?
